questions.question:
Choose the correct option to fill ?1 and ?2 so that the program below prints an input string in reverse order. Assume that the input string is terminated by a new line character.

void reverse(void) {
    int c;
    if(?1) reverse();
    ?2
}
main() {
    printf("Enter text");
    printf("\n");
    reverse();
}

A. ?1 is (c = getchar()) != '\n'
   ?2 is putchar(c);
B. ?1 is (c = getchar()) != '\n'
   ?2 is putchar(c);
C. ?1 is (c = getchar()) != '\n'
   ?2 is putchar(c);
D. ?1 is ((c = getchar()) != '\n')
   ?2 is putchar(c);

steps.apply:
?1 must read a character AND check it is not newline in one expression: (c = getchar()) != '\n'. This assigns the character to c and continues recursion if not end-of-line.
?2 must print the character AFTER the recursive call returns: putchar(c).
Option B matches: ?1 is (c = getchar()) != '\n', ?2 is putchar(c);

questions.question:
Consider the following C code segment.

int a, b, c = 0;
void prtFun(void);
int main()
{
    static int a = 1; /* Line 1 */
    prtFun();
    a += 1;
    prtFun();
    printf("\n %d %d ", a, b);
}
void prtFun(void)
{
    static int a = 2; /* Line 2 */
    int b = 1;
    a += ++b;
    printf("\n %d %d ", a, b);
}

What output will be generated by the given code segment?

A.  3 1       B.  4 1
    4 1           5 1
    4 1            5 0

C.  4 2       D.  4 2
    6 1           6 1
    6 0            2 0
